Penalized regression - Elastic net

All pair-wise interactions between the inputs

First we define the search grid:

my_lambda <- penalty(range = c(-10.5, 2), trans = log_trans())
my_alpha <- mixture(range = c(0.1, 1.0))
enet_grid <- grid_regular(my_lambda, my_alpha, 
                          levels = c(penalty = 75, mixture = 5))

enet_grid %>% glimpse()

Then we define the elastic net model:

enet_spec <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet", 
             # glmnet specific options
             intercept = TRUE, standardize.response = TRUE, standardize = TRUE,
             path_values = exp(seq(-10.5, 2, length.out = 75)))

neural network using Torch

Fisrt define the torch version of dataset:

torch_dataset <- dataset(
  
  name = "torch_dataset",
  
  initialize = function(df) {
    self$data <- self$prepare_data(df)
  },
  
  .getitem = function(index) {
    
    x <- self$data[index, 1:-2]
    y <- self$data[index, -1]
    
    list(x, y)
  },
  
  .length = function() {
    self$data$size()[[1]]
  },
  
  prepare_data = function(df) {
    
    input <- na.omit(df) 

    input <- as.matrix(input)
    torch_tensor(input)
  }
)

Split train and test with 70% and 30%:

set.seed(2021)
train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(ready_x_A), round(nrow(ready_x_A)*0.7))

torch_train_ds <- torch_dataset(ready_x_A[train_indices, ])

valid_dl$.length()
## [1] 36

Define the network structure:

torch_net <- nn_module(
  "regNet",
  initialize = function() {
    self$fc1 <- nn_linear(43, 64)
    self$fc2 <- nn_linear(64, 1)
  },
  forward = function(x) {
    x %>% 
      self$fc1() %>% 
      nnf_relu() %>% 
      self$fc2() 
  }
)

torch_model <- torch_net()

Train the model. The result has some problems. so I comment it out for now:

{r, torch_train_nn} optimizer <- optim_adam(torch_model$parameters, lr = 0.01)

for (epoch in 1:10) {

torch_model$train() train_losses <- c()

coro::loop(for (b in train_dl) {

optimizer$zero_grad()
output <- torch_model(b[[1]])
loss <- nnf_nll_loss(output, b[[2]])

loss$backward()
optimizer$step()

train_losses <- c(train_losses, loss$item())

})

torch_model$eval() valid_losses <- c()

coro::loop(for (b in valid_dl) {

output <- torch_model(b[[1]])
loss <- nnf_nll_loss(output, b[[2]])
valid_losses <- c(valid_losses, loss$item())

})

cat(sprintf(MSE at epoch %d: training: %3.3f, validation: %3.3f, epoch, mean(train_losses), mean(valid_losses))) }

Neural Network

Build neural network using mlp:

nnet_spec <- mlp(hidden_units = tune(), penalty = tune(), epochs = 1000) %>% 
  set_engine("nnet", MaxNWts = 2500, trace=FALSE) %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

Define neural network workflow:

nnet_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(nnet_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(bp_additive)

Tune the model using Bayesian optimization:

nn_set <- parameters(nnet_wflow)
#nn_set <- nn_set %>%
#  update(hidden_units = hidden_units(c(0L, 10L)),
#         penalty = penalty(c(-2L,2L)))

set.seed(2021)
nn_res <- nnet_wflow %>%
  tune_bayes(resamples = cv_folds,
             param_info = nn_set,
             initial = 5,
             iter = 10,
             metrics = my_metrics,
             control = control_bayes(no_improve = 30, verbose = TRUE))

Random forest

Define the model and the workflow:

rf_spec <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(), min_n = tune(), trees = 1000) %>% 
  set_engine("ranger") %>% 
  set_mode('regression')

rf_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(rf_spec) %>% 
  add_formula(response ~ .)

Tune the model using Bayesian optimization:

rf_set <-  rf_spec %>% parameters() %>% finalize(ready_x_A)

set.seed(2021)
rf_res <- rf_wflow %>%
  tune_bayes(resamples = cv_folds,
             param_info = rf_set,
             metrics = my_metrics,
             initial = 5,
             iter = 10,
             control = control_bayes(no_improve = 5, verbose = TRUE))

Support Vector Machine (SVM)

Define SVM model and workflow:

svm_rbf_spec <- svm_rbf(cost = tune(), rbf_sigma = tune(), margin = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("kernlab") %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

svm_rbf_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(svm_rbf_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(bp_additive)

Tune SVM using racing with ANOVA:

rbf_grid <- crossing(rbf_sigma = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.4, 0.8, 1.25, 1.5),
                     cost = c(0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100),
                     margin = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1.0))

svm_rbf_res <- tune_race_anova(

K-nearest neighbors

Create model and workflow:

knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune(), weight_func = tune()) %>%
  set_mode("regression") %>%
  set_engine("kknn")

knn_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(knn_spec) %>% 
  add_formula(response ~ .)

Tune KNN using racing with ANOVA:

knn_grid <- crossing(neighbors = seq(1,50),
                     weight_func = c("rectangular", "triangular", "epanechnikov", "biweight", "triweight", "cos", "inv", "gaussian", "rank", "optimal")) 

set.seed(2021)
knn_res <- tune_race_anova(
  knn_wflow,
  resamples = cv_folds,
  grid = knn_grid,
  metrics = my_metrics
)

Model comparison

all_cv_summaries %>% 
  mutate(wflow_id = forcats::fct_reorder(wflow_id, mean, min)) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = wflow_id)) +
  geom_linerange(mapping = aes(ymin = mean - 2*std_err,
                               ymax = mean + 2*std_err,
                               group = interaction(.metric, wflow_id)),
                 color = 'grey', size = 1.) +
  geom_linerange(mapping = aes(ymin = mean - 1*std_err,
                               ymax = mean + 1*std_err,
                               group = interaction(.metric, wflow_id)),
                 color = 'red', size = 1.2) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(y = mean),
             color = 'red', size = 2.5) +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(~.metric, scales = "free_x") +
  labs(y = "performance metric value", x ="") +
  theme_bw()

From the plot we can see the neural network model performs the best base on MAE, RMSE and R-Squared.
